\section{The Thiasos as Ally}

Every Runekeeper is bound to a Thiasos—a fragment of their Patron's attention made manifest. For a traditional Runekeeper, the Thiasos is often a familiar: a small creature that chitters from a shoulder, a spirit that drifts at the edge of vision, a bound entity that serves as a witness and a warning.

For a Body Runekeeper, the Thiasos is different.

It is not a pet. It is not a servant. It is an \textit{ally}. It fights beside them. It carries their burdens. It watches their back in a way that no book-bound Rite ever could.

\subsection{Core Rules}

A Thiasos is a companion with its own traits. It has:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Cap} — A measure of its power and effectiveness (typically 2-5).
\item \textbf{Harm} — How much damage it can sustain before being incapacitated.
\item \textbf{Traits} — Special abilities unique to its type.
\item \textbf{Actions} — A Thiasos may act independently once per scene (the Runekeeper's action). Otherwise, it requires a command (the Runekeeper's action) to perform a significant task.
\end{itemize}

A Thiasos counts as a witness for Rites that require one. It sees, it remembers, and it can testify—though its testimony may be limited to growls, chirps, or the ringing of a bell.

If a Thiasos is reduced to 0 Harm, it is incapacitated. It does not die immediately, but it cannot act or witness until healed. A Thiasos heals naturally over downtime (one week per point of Harm), or can be healed faster with Medicine, magic, or (in the case of constructs) Craft.

\subsection{Living Thiasos}

Living Thiasos are creatures. They breathe, eat, sleep, and bleed. They are loyal, but they are not mindless. They have their own fears, preferences, and instincts.

\subsubsection{Warhorse}

\textbf{Patrons:} Oath of Flame \& Light, Aveh, The Traveler

\textbf{Cap:} 3-5

\textbf{Harm:} 5

\textbf{Traits:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{Swift:} +1 die to chase or escape rolls.
\item \textit{Trample:} When the Runekeeper charges, the warhorse may also attack (Harm 2 to one target in Close range).
\item \textit{Loyal:} The warhorse will not flee while the Runekeeper is mounted.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Spirit-Hound}

\textbf{Patrons:} Mykkiel, The Sealed Gate, Varnek Karn

\textbf{Cap:} 2-4

\textbf{Harm:} 4

\textbf{Traits:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{Tracker:} +2 dice to track a target by scent.
\item \textit{Spirit Sense:} Can detect invisible or incorporeal creatures within Near range.
\item \textit{Bound to Oath:} If the Runekeeper breaks a sworn oath, the spirit-hound whines and refuses to act for one scene.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Wolf-Ancestor}

\textbf{Patrons:} Grimmir, The Savage Heart

\textbf{Cap:} 3-4

\textbf{Harm:} 4

\textbf{Traits:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{Pack Hunter:} When the Runekeeper attacks a target, the wolf-ancestor gains +1 die to attack the same target.
\item \textit{Howl:} Once per scene, the wolf-ancestor howls. Allies gain +1 die to resist fear for the scene.
\item \textit{Ancestral Memory:} The wolf-ancestor recalls the names of the Runekeeper's ancestors (GM may provide hints or lore).
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Fungal Familiar}

\textbf{Patrons:} The Carrion-King

\textbf{Cap:} 2-3

\textbf{Harm:} 3

\textbf{Traits:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{Spore Cloud:} Once per scene, the familiar releases a cloud of spores. Enemies in Close range test Endurance (DV 3) or suffer -1 die to physical actions for one exchange.
\item \textit{Decay Sense:} The familiar can detect rot, decay, or corruption within Near range.
\item \textit{Regenerative:} The familiar regains 1 Harm per day (faster than natural healing).
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Clockwork Construct}

\textbf{Patrons:} Clockwork Monad

\textbf{Cap:} 2-4

\textbf{Harm:} 5

\textbf{Traits:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{Mechanical Precision:} The construct gains +1 die to Craft or Tinker actions.
\item \textit{Self-Repair:} Once per downtime, the Runekeeper may repair 1 Harm to the construct with a Craft test (DV 3).
\item \textit{Iterative Upgrade:} The Runekeeper may install temporary enhancements (once per session, gain +1 die to one action performed by the construct).
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Hollowed Child or Heartless Bird}

\textbf{Patrons:} The High Mother

\textbf{Cap:} 2

\textbf{Harm:} Cannot be harmed by mundane means

\textbf{Traits:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{Silent Witness:} The Hollowed counts as a witness for all Rites. It never blinks.
\item \textit{Memory Keeper:} The Hollowed records every debt it witnesses. The Runekeeper may consult it to recall a forgotten promise or obligation.
\item \textit{Unsettling Presence:} Animals and children are disturbed by the Hollowed. Social rolls involving them suffer -1 die if the Hollowed is visible.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Sentient Thiasos (Optional Rule)}

Not every Thiasos breathes. Some are objects—weapons, shields, tools, or tokens touched by the Patron's will. A sentient Thiasos cannot move on its own (unless animated by a Rite or talent), but it can speak, sense, and remember.

Sentient Thiasos are detailed in a separate chapter. They are rare, memorable, and often opinionated.

\subsection{Thiasos and Obligation}

When a Body Runekeeper marks Obligation, the Thiasos may also bear a mark. A warhorse develops a limp. A spirit-hound's glow dims. A sword's edge dulls.

The Runekeeper may transfer Fatigue to their Thiasos (Shared Burden talent), but the Thiasos becomes Winded (-1 die to all actions) for the rest of the scene. This is a choice, not a requirement. Some Runekeepers refuse to burden their allies.

\subsection{Losing a Thiasos}

A Thiasos can be killed, destroyed, or lost.

If a living Thiasos dies, the Runekeeper marks 2 Obligation immediately (the Patron's disappointment) and gains the Condition \textit{Bereaved} (-1 die to all rolls involving trust or loyalty) until they acquire a new Thiasos.

If a sentient Thiasos is destroyed, the Runekeeper loses all Rites engraved on it (if it served as a Codex). They may repair it with significant downtime and a Craft test (DV 5), or they may find a new Thiasos.

Acquiring a new Thiasos is a downtime project. The Runekeeper must:
\begin{itemize}
\item Find a suitable creature or object (GM discretion).
\item Perform a bonding ritual (one day, requires a threshold and a witness).
\item Mark 1 Obligation (the Patron's fee for a new ally).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{The Thiasos as Witness}

A Thiasos is always a witness. It sees the Runekeeper's Rites, hears their oaths, and remembers their debts. This is true even if the Thiasos cannot speak.

In a hedge-court, a Thiasos's presence may suffice as a witness where no human witness is available. The judge may not like it, but the law is the law.

The thread held. The water carried. That is not a Rite. That is grace.
